    <!-- MAXIMISE LONGEVITY -->
    <section class="section alt">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="feature-article fade-up">
          <div class="fa-media"><img src="{{ 'kit-gift.jpg' | asset_url }}" alt="Applying fragrance to the skin" /></div>
          <div class="fa-body">
            <span class="bl-cat">Longevity</span>
            <h2>Maximise Longevity on Skin &amp; Clothing</h2>
            <p>Caring for your fragrance does not stop at the bottle. Apply to moisturised skin at the pulse points, let it dry down without rubbing, and layer a matching oil beneath your spray for staying power. Fabric holds scent even longer than skin — a light mist on a scarf or collar carries your fragrance through a long evening, though delicate silks should be tested first.</p>
            <p>In Gulf heat, re-applying a lighter scent midday often works better than over-spraying in the morning.</p>
            <a class="btn-ghost" href="/pages/buying-guides">Choose a longer-lasting scent <span class="mi" aria-hidden="true">arrow_forward</span></a>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- FAQ -->
    <section class="faq" id="faq">
      <div class="faq-inner">
        <div class="faq-head fade-up">
          <span class="label">Care &amp; Troubleshooting</span>
          <h2 class="sec-title">Care Questions, <em>Answered</em></h2>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-list fade-up">
          <details class="faq-item">
            <summary class="faq-q">Can I store perfume in the fridge?<span class="mi" aria-hidden="true">add</span></summary>
            <div class="faq-a">You can, and in a hot climate like the UAE a dedicated cool spot or wine fridge (around 10–15°C) can extend a fragrance's life. Avoid the freezer and avoid constant moving in and out, as repeated temperature changes do more harm than steady cool storage.</div>
          </details>
          <details class="faq-item">
            <summary class="faq-q">Why has my perfume changed colour or smell?<span class="mi" aria-hidden="true">add</span></summary>
            <div class="faq-a">Darkening or a slightly sour top note usually points to oxidation from heat, light or air exposure. The base notes often still perform well. Going forward, store the bottle sealed, cool and dark to slow any further change.</div>
          </details>
          <details class="faq-item">
            <summary class="faq-q">How long does an opened bottle of perfume last?<span class="mi" aria-hidden="true">add</span></summary>
            <div class="faq-a">Stored properly, most opened fragrances stay beautiful for three to five years, and richer oud and amber compositions can last even longer. Poor storage — not age alone — is what shortens a bottle's life.</div>
          </details>
          <details class="faq-item">
            <summary class="faq-q">My atomiser stopped spraying — what do I do?<span class="mi" aria-hidden="true">add</span></summary>
            <div class="faq-a">First, remove the cap and pump a few times to clear an air lock. If it is still stuck, rinse the spray head in warm water, dry it completely and refit. Forcing a clogged nozzle is the most common cause of a broken pump, so be gentle.</div>
          </details>
          <details class="faq-item">
            <summary class="faq-q">Should I keep the original box?<span class="mi" aria-hidden="true">add</span></summary>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes. The box is the simplest, most effective protection against light and dust, and it keeps your fragrance in ideal condition between wears. It is also useful proof of authenticity should you ever gift or resell.</div>
          </details>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

